<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/Forum21/HTML/002196.html">
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#000050"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#FFFFFF" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Fiter</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Hello everyone. Please take the time to answer the following questions. Thanks!<P>Where are the places not to use painbringer because of its area effect?<P><BR>What is the damage range for you level 30th warriors using 1 handed slahs please indicate your total strength and weapon used.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Darodar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Generally you don't want to use PB in any dungeon where you have mobs above or below you.  The obvious choices here would be unrest, befallen, highkeep, and blackburrow although you probably won't be anywhere near blackburrow at 30 and if you are a train won't hurt you too bad  <IMG SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/wink.gif"><P>You also don't want to use it if you have an enchanter in the group, but the enchanter will probably let you know real quick to switch it out.<P>The only other place I know for sure is in GFay under kelethin.  I was running through one day and smacked a decaying skeleton for the hell of it and PB proc'ed.  I proceded to run to crushbone with 3 or 4 very upset merchants on my heels.<P>There are probably other zones, these are just the ones I know of.<P>Darodar Steelstorm<BR>41 Human Warrior<BR>Prexus</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Kupa</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">yep, be VERY careful about non-aggro NPCs who might be in AE range. I saw a guy in rivervale attacked by that mutt Mangler... riposted... Fleshripper proc'd... merchants, guards and PoD aggroed... he died FAST.<P>Just walking about innocently with an AE weapon equipped can be a problem... even if you don't use it =P<P>------------------<BR>Kupa FrostHeart<BR>37th Barbarian Warrior<BR>Fennin Ro</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Flair</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Add Bards to your list.  A bard sleeping a pile of MOBs will berate you for quite some time for using PB/FR in their group.<P>Its also best not to use them when pulling inside...unless you like 4-5 MOBs (this includes Perma, Guk, CT, Paw, Runnyeye, Sol A etc.)<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Ulthumbra</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Pfft!<P>You get a weapon like Painbringer and want to be cautious about using it? 30th level and looking for ways to please the other classes?<P>You got the Painbringer, let everyone around you beware. Let THEM adjust to you. It's a fact around 30 most casters have never grouped with a warrior, so they're the ones that have a few things to learn at that point. Your job never changes.  <P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Hivemind</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Having a lot of experience with grouping with enchanters, if you keep AE procing and disrupting their mez spells then they will adjust.  They will adjust by either leaving or getting you kicked out of the group.  Your only hope would be that the enchanter or bard don´t actually know what should happen and let you get away with it for a while.<P>The list of situations where the AE procing weapons suck includes (but is not limited to)-<BR>- Fighting mutiple mobs where you have an enchanter or bard trying to do crowd control<BR>- Fighting in an area with close in non-aggro creatures that will be provoked to attack by the proc (this includes those death holes that have multiple levels since vertical distance is not counted).  The majority of locations where you will be fighting fall in to this category.<P>Situations where they are good are-<BR>- You are too low a level for the weapon to proc.  You have probably got a weapon that has a great damage to delay ratio for your level and no nasty side effects to ruin your day.<BR>- You are fighting against one target and there are not other targets nearby (of course things have a habit of wandering close at the worst times).  Then the proc becomes the equivalent of a nice safe DD.<BR>- You are fighting against multiple creatures, nobody is doing crowd control and there are no other target nearby to be woken up.  In this situation the AE procing weapons are great.  They help you keep all the creatures on you and they build up the damage.  Shame this doesn't happen too often.<P>What is really, really a shame is that the AE procs can't be manually triggered.  At the start of combat it would be great to be able to look around, check that there are no nearby non-aggro mobs and trigger the AE to build up the hate list and get things locked on to you, then let the crowd control go ahead and not have to worry about non-aggros getting too close.  If crowd control goes down the toilet or the cleric gets mobbed it would also be a great time to be able to AE, not have to rely on the vagaries of chance letting it happen then.  A weapon with unlimited charges of an AE attack that had a 5 or 10 minute delay built in would be very useful to me.<P>Hivemind (aka Grak, Troll Warrior)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Caea</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Yeah, I like that guy that say screw the enchanter or bard, let them adjust....<P>I mean really, a group is going to give up clarity for you, no problem. That mana song is not really anygood anyway, right?<P>I mostly play a monk, one of the 3 classes that does not spend most of its time on EQ meding, and I would boot your ass out faster than snot for that.<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Flair</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">ADJUST??<P>Are you nuts?  My Bard is my best guild buddy (Enchanters & Clerics not far behind).  If Bard/Enchanter is around you want them on crowd control or you want to die in a tough spot....<P>Or perhaps you should just solo *smile*  <P>But hey, do what you want.  EQ is a very darwinistic game...tends to work itself out every night.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Flair</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Also answer to Q2:<P>Dam Range (Str 154/Lvl 32):<P>6/23 Dragoon Dagger 4-19 (max crit in high 30s...37-39 I think)<P>10/38 Shield of Slain Uni 12-28 (max hit 43-44)<P>6/22 Silvery War Axe 4-19 </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
</IFRAME>
